  <article class="container longform">
    <h1>What is the Meaning of Practice?</h1>
    <p class="lead">Practice means living the Law every day: chant daimoku, do Gongyo, attend temple, and study. Through consistent effort, we transform our life-state and reveal inherent Buddhahood.</p>

    <h2>Practice for oneself and for others</h2>
    <p>Nichiren taught that practice has two wheels—practice for oneself (chanting, Gongyo, study) and practice for others (encouraging people to embrace the Law). When both wheels turn, life accelerates toward happiness.</p>

    <h2>Daily rhythm of practice</h2>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Daimoku:</strong> Chant Nam-Myoho-Renge-Kyo morning and evening with clear determinations.</li>
      <li><strong>Gongyo:</strong> Recite the Lotus Sutra passages to harmonize with the Three Treasures.</li>
      <li><strong>Study:</strong> Read the Gosho and temple guidance to deepen understanding.</li>
      <li><strong>Temple participation:</strong> Attend Oko, meetings, and volunteer activities to strengthen unity.</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>Practice reveals proof</h2>
    <p>When we practice consistently, benefit appears in two forms: conspicuous (immediate victories) and inconspicuous (steady inner growth). Recording victories and sharing them during meetings reinforces conviction and inspires others.</p>

    <div class="notice">
      <p>If practice feels difficult, return to the basics—chant earnestly, seek guidance, and support someone else. Effort rooted in faith always opens a path forward.</p>
    </div>

